{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513081"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:05:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:05:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12005"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12005"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.08,0.06,0.08,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4592"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59847"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4592"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12005"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45264"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"203"},{"type":"tags","id":"1737"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18837"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59847"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to her General Practice because she has been experiencing panic attacks over the last three months. During each episode, she feels her heart racing, her chest tightens, she feels faint and nauseated and has to sit down in a quiet room for it to stop. She is unable to pin point any identifiable triggers. She notices herself constantly ruminating about when the next one might happen, and the fear of experiencing subsequent panic attacks while out in public has held her back from going out as often as she would like to. The attacks are intermittent and unpredictable. She does not have a history of other mental illnesses, and does not have a history of recreational drug use, smoking or drinking alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Panic disorder","Agoraphobia","Panic attack","Generalised anxiety disorder","Social anxiety disorder"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPanic disorder \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most likely diagnosis. While the physiological symptoms described are consistent with that of a panic attack, the recurring nature of these attacks, the unexpected nature of these attacks and the fear associated with experiencing another panic attack, resulting in avoidant behavior, render this more of a panic disorder than a panic attack.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAgoraphobia \u003C/strong\u003EAgoraphobia is characterised classically by an irrational and intense fear of being in crowded spaces and in public where escape might be difficult, resulting in avoidance of these spaces. However in this case, the fear of being in crowded spaces stems more from the pre-existing fear of having the attack in public, as opposed to a fear of being in crowds itself. Many individuals with agoraphobia do develop it as a consequence of repeated panic attacks and in this case a dual diagnosis is made.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPanic attack \u003C/strong\u003Echaracterises a brief episode of intense anxiety marked by symptoms such as chest tightness, shortness of breath, diaphoresis, chills, palpitations. Panic attacks can occur as part of a wide variety of disorders such as major depression, panic disorder, some personality disorders and all anxiety disorders. However, the other symptoms present and the circumstances and frequency of panic attacks have to be carefully examined to make the diagnosis. In this case, the patient has been having panic attacks but this is not a diagnosis or disorder per se. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneralised anxiety disorder \u003C/strong\u003Eis characterised by intense fear and worry about a range of things, for more than six months, for most days than not. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003ESocial anxiety disorder \u003C/strong\u003Echaracterised by fear that is out of proportion, associated with social situations in which the individual is susceptible to scrutiny, such as in the context of public speaking, eating in big groups of people or initiating conversations with new people, resulting in functional impairment. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Panic disorder is characterized by recurrent unexpected panic attacks plus persistent concern about future attacks or maladaptive behavior changes.","A panic attack is a discrete episode of intense fear with physical symptoms, but is not itself a diagnosis.","While agoraphobia commonly co-occurs with panic disorder, it represents a distinct fear of situations where escape might be difficult."],"references":["Cackovic C, Nazir S, Marwaha R. Panic Disorder. [Updated 2022 Jun 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430973/","Balaram K, Marwaha R. Agoraphobia. [Updated 2022 Jun 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554387/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45264"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12005"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45264"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-09T10:59:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-09T11:01:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4592"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59847"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0